                <div style="width:100%; background-color: transparent; box-sizing:border-box;">
                    <h3 style="width:100%; font-family:'Helvetica Neue', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif;font-size:16px;margin:0;padding-bottom:16px;font-weight:700;color:#28121F;line-height:20px;text-transform:capitalize;letter-spacing:-0.32px;text-align:left;box-sizing:border-box;">GETESA wants to expand its telecom infrastructure, launch mobile money in Equatorial Guinea</h3>
                    <div style="font-family:'Helvetica Neue', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif;font-weight: 400;font-size:16px;line-height:25.6px;margin:0;padding-bottom:16px;box-sizing:border-box;">
<figure style="width: 100%;padding-bottom:16px;text-align:left;margin:0">


                        <a href="https://techcabal.com/category/newsletters/tc-daily/">
                             <img decoding="async" 
     	loading="lazy" src="https://c76c7bbc41.mjedge.net/wp-content/uploads/tc/2026/03/feel-me-think-about-it.gif" width="100%" height="auto" style="object-fit: cover"></a>
                         <figcaption style="color:#808080;font-size:12px;font-family:'Helvetica Neue', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif;line-height:19.8px;padding-top:6px;font-weight:400">Image Source: Tenor</figcaption>
                    </figure>
                        
<p style="padding:5px 0;margin:0;">GETESA, Equatorial Guinea&#8217;s state-owned telecom operator, appears to have looked at its network and decided it was time for a factory reset.</p>
<p style="padding:5px 0;margin:0;">The telco has <a href="https://www.ecofinagency.com/news-digital/0106-56057-equatorial-guinea-s-state-telecom-operator-targets-5g-fiber-and-mobile-money" style="text-decoration: underline; color: #b61313 !important;">unveiled a 12-month modernisation plan</a> that includes 5G, expanded fibre infrastructure, public Wi-Fi, eSIM technology, and a new mobile money platform called Getesa Money. It also wants to revive a national fibre-optic network that has largely been reserved for the country&#8217;s electricity utility.</p>
<p style="padding:5px 0;margin:0;"><strong>The ambition is understandable.</strong> After the telecom firm conducted an audit, it found ageing equipment, slow Internet speeds, network congestion, and weak technical planning were crippling its service quality to customers. More customers complained, and GETESA seems to be actively heeding their call.&nbsp;</p>
<p style="padding:5px 0;margin:0;">For a country <a href="https://datareportal.com/reports/digital-2025-equatorial-guinea" style="text-decoration: underline; color: #b61313 !important;">where 60.4% of the population is already online</a>, the upgrade is less about getting people connected and more about improving what happens after they connect. Faster networks could support everything from streaming and cloud services to digital payments and online businesses.</p>
<p style="padding:5px 0;margin:0;"><strong>The most interesting addition may be mobile money. </strong>GETESA&rsquo;s mobile money plan is also notable because in Africa, telco-backed operators&mdash;spanning players like Orange Money, VodaPay, and Telkom Pay&mdash;are becoming a dime a dozen.&nbsp;</p>
<p style="padding:5px 0;margin:0;">Across Africa, telecom operators have discovered that connectivity is only half the business. The other half is moving money. If GETESA can pair better coverage with financial services, it could become more than a telco. It could become a bigger part of how Equatorial Guineans communicate, transact, and access digital services.</p>
<p style="padding:5px 0;margin:0;">The challenge, as always, is execution. Announcing 5G is easy. Building the infrastructure to make it useful is the hard part.</p>
</div>
